    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThere's no clean way (that I can find) to determine the gui front end. Looking for a way to determine the client, like in a `UIEnter` handler.  Would use the info now so the client name can be put into the title bar. This is especially useful when experimenting with different `gui`s.\n\nI'm guessing some info might also be for other uses. For example, client capabilities. Neither `neovide` nor `goneovim` support `&mousemoveevent`. It would be useful to know this so, for example, a popup compatibility layer could generate an error if a popup feature is requested that requires `&mousemoveevent.\n\n@justinmk #27949 may be loosely related. In particular for a `gui` client, maybe something like `nvim_get_client_info()`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nSomething like following hack works, but also needs a deferred check after about a second because it takes a while for `Goneovim` to warm up.\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"UIEnter\", {\n    callback = function()\n        if vim.fn.exists(\":NeovideFocus\") > 0 then\n            set_app(\"Neovide\")\n        elseif vim.fn.exists(\":GonvimFilerOpen\") > 0 then\n            set_app(\"Goneovim\")\n        else\n            set_app(\"Nvim\")\n        end\n        return true\n    end\n})\n```\n",
